[src:cnapp/application-security] Web Application Security Tools are specialized tools for working with HTTP traffic, e.g., Web application firewalls.
[src:cnapp/application-security] Different approaches will find different subsets of the security vulnerabilities lurking in an application and are most effective at different times in the software lifecycle.
[src:cnapp/application-security] They each represent different tradeoffs of time, effort, cost and vulnerabilities found.
[src:cnapp/application-security] The Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) provides free and open resources.
[src:cnapp/application-security] It is led by a non-profit called The OWASP Foundation.
[src:cnapp/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 - 2017 results from recent research based on comprehensive data compiled from over 40 partner organizations.
[src:cnapp/application-security] This data revealed approximately 2.3 million vulnerabilities across over 50,000 applications.
[src:cnapp/application-security] The OWASP Top 10 Proactive Controls 2024 is a list of security techniques every software architect and developer should know and heed.
[src:cnapp/application-security] Security testing techniques scour for vulnerabilities or security holes in applications.
[src:cnapp/application-security] These vulnerabilities leave applications open to exploitation.
[src:cnapp/application-security] Ideally, security testing is implemented throughout the entire software development life cycle (SDLC) so that vulnerabilities may be addressed in a timely and thorough manner.
[src:cnapp/application-security] There are many kinds of automated tools for identifying vulnerabilities in applications.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:cnapp/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] In software engineering, **containerization** is operating-system-level virtualization or application-level virtualization over multiple resources so that software applications can run in isolated user spaces called *containers* in any cloud or non-cloud environment, regardless of type or vendor.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] The term "container" has different meanings in different contexts, and it is important to ensure that the intended definition aligns with the audience's understanding.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Each *container* is basically a fully functional and portable cloud or non-cloud computing environment surrounding the application and keeping it independent of other environments running in parallel.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Individually, each container simulates a different software application and runs isolated processes by bundling related configuration files, libraries and dependencies.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] But, collectively, multiple containers share a common operating system kernel (OS).
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] In recent times, containerization technology has been widely adopted by cloud computing platforms like Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google Cloud Platform, and IBM Cloud.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Containerization has also been pursued by the U.S.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Department of Defense as a way of more rapidly developing and fielding software updates, with first application in its F-22 air superiority fighter.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Container orchestration or container management is mostly used in the context of application containers.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Implementations providing such orchestration include Kubernetes and Docker swarm.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] This includes functionality to create a cluster, to upgrade the software or repair it, balance the load between existing instances, scale by starting or stopping instances to adapt to the number of users, to log activities and monitor produced logs or the application itself by querying sensors.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Open-source implementations of such software include OKD and Rancher.
[src:cnapp/container-virtualization] Quite a number of companies provide container cluster management as a managed service, like Alibaba, Amazon, Google, and Microsoft.
[src:cnapp/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:cnapp/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:cnapp/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:cnapp/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:cnapp/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:cnapp/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:cnapp/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:cnapp/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:cnapp/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:cnapp/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:cnapp/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:cnapp/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:cnapp/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:cnapp/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:cnapp/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:cnapp/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:cnapp/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:cnapp/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:cnapp/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:cnapp/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:cnapp/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:cnapp/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:cnapp/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:cnapp/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:cnapp/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:cnapp/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:cnapp/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:cnapp/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:cnapp/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:cnapp/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:cnapp/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:cnapp/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:cnapp/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:cnapp/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:cnapp/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:cnapp/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:cnapp/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:cnapp/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:cnapp/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:cnapp/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:cnapp/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:cnapp/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:cnapp/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:cnapp/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:cnapp/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:cnapp/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:cnapp/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:cnapp/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:cnapp/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:cnapp/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:cnapp/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:cnapp/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:cnapp/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:cnapp/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:cnapp/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:cnapp/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:cnapp/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:cnapp/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:cnapp/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:cnapp/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:cnapp/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:cnapp/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:cnapp/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:cnapp/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:cnapp/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:cnapp/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:cnapp/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:cnapp/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:cnapp/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:cnapp/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:cnapp/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:cnapp/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:cnapp/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:cnapp/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:cnapp/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:cnapp/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:cnapp/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] In computer security, a **vulnerability** is a flaw or weakness in a system's design, implementation, or management that can be exploited by a malicious actor to compromise its security.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts to achieve complete correctness, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs where the system does not behave as expected.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] If the bug could enable an attacker to compromise the confidentiality, integrity, or availability of system resources, it can be considered a vulnerability.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Insecure software development practices as well as design factors such as complexity can increase the burden of vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management includes identifying systems and prioritizing which are most important, scanning for vulnerabilities, and taking action to secure the system.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability management typically is a combination of remediation, mitigation, and acceptance.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can be scored for severity according to the Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) and added to vulnerability databases such as the Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE) database.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] As of April 2026, more than 327,000 vulnerabilities had been recorded in the CVE database.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] A vulnerability is initiated when it is introduced into hardware or software.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] It becomes active and exploitable when the software or hardware containing the vulnerability is running.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability may be discovered by the administrator, vendor, or a third party.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Publicly disclosing the vulnerability (through a patch or otherwise) is associated with an increased risk of compromise, as attackers can use this knowledge to target existing systems before patches are implemented.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities will eventually end when the system is either patched or removed from use.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Despite a system administrator's best efforts, virtually all hardware and software contain bugs.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] If a bug creates a security risk, it is called a vulnerability.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Software patches are often released to fix identified vulnerabilities, but zero-days are still liable for exploitation.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities vary in their ability to be exploited by malicious actors, and the actual risk is dependent on the nature of the vulnerability as well as the value of the surrounding system.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Although some vulnerabilities can only be used for denial-of-service attacks, more dangerous ones allow the attacker to perform code injection without the user's awareness.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Only a minority of vulnerabilities allow for privilege escalation, which is typically necessary for more severe attacks.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Without a vulnerability, an exploit typically cannot gain access.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] It is also possible for malware to be installed directly, without an exploit, through social engineering or poor physical security such as an unlocked door or exposed port.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Poor software development practices can affect the likelihood of introducing vulnerabilities to a code base.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Lack of knowledge or training regarding secure software development, excessive pressure to deliver, or an excessively complex code base can all allow vulnerabilities to be introduced and left unnoticed.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] These factors can also be exacerbated if security is not prioritized by the company culture.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Inadequate code reviews can also lead to missed bugs, but there are also static code analysis tools that can be used during the code review process to help find some vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] DevOps, a development workflow that emphasizes automated testing and deployment to speed up the deployment of new features, often requires that many developers be granted access to change configurations, which can lead to deliberate or inadvertent inclusion of vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Compartmentalizing dependencies, which is often part of DevOps workflows, can reduce the attack surface by paring down dependencies to only what is necessary.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] If software as a service is used, rather than the organization's own hardware and software, the organization is dependent on the cloud services provider to prevent vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Access control vulnerabilities enable an attacker to access a system that is supposed to be restricted to them, or engage in privilege escalation.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] When the system fails to handle and exceptional or unanticipated condition correctly, an attacker can exploit the situation to gain access.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Configuration vulnerability come into existence when configuration settings cause risks to the system security, leading to such faults as unpatched software or file system permissions that do not sufficiently restrict access.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] A race condition—when timing or other external factors change the outcome and lead to inconsistent or unpredictable results—can cause a vulnerability.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Deliberate security bugs can be introduced during or after manufacturing and cause the integrated circuit not to behave as expected under certain specific circumstances.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Testing for security bugs in hardware is quite difficult due to limited time and the complexity of twenty-first century chips, while the globalization of design and manufacturing has increased the opportunity for these bugs to be introduced by malicious actors.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Although operating system vulnerabilities vary depending on the operating system in use, a common problem is privilege escalation bugs that enable the attacker to gain more access than they should be allowed.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Open-source operating systems such as Linux and Android have a freely accessible source code and allow anyone to contribute, which could enable the introduction of vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] However, the same vulnerabilities also occur in proprietary operating systems such as Microsoft Windows and Apple operating systems.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] All reputable vendors of operating systems provide patches regularly.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Client–server applications are downloaded onto the end user's computers and are typically updated less frequently than web applications.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Unlike web applications, they interact directly with a user's operating system.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Because they are inherently less secure than other applications, they are a leading source of data breaches and other security incidents.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] There is little evidence about the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of different cyberattack prevention measures.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Although estimating the risk of an attack is not straightforward, the mean time to breach and expected cost can be considered to determine the priority for remediating or mitigating an identified vulnerability and whether it is cost effective to do so.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Although attention to security can reduce the risk of attack, achieving perfect security for a complex system is impossible, and many security measures have unacceptable cost or usability downsides.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] For example, reducing the complexity and functionality of the system is effective at reducing the attack surface.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Successful vulnerability management usually involves a combination of remediation (closing a vulnerability), mitigation (increasing the difficulty, and reducing the consequences, of exploits), and accepting some residual risk.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Often a defense in depth strategy is used for multiple barriers to attack.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Some organizations scan for only the highest-risk vulnerabilities as this enables prioritization in the context of lacking the resources to fix every vulnerability.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Increasing expenses is likely to have diminishing returns.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Remediation fixes vulnerabilities, for example by downloading a software patch.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability scanners are typically unable to detect zero-day vulnerabilities, but are more effective at finding known vulnerabilities based on a database.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] These systems can find some known vulnerabilities and advise fixes, such as a patch.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] However, they have limitations including false positives.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities can only be exploited when they are active-the software in which they are embedded is actively running on the system.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Before the code containing the vulnerability is configured to run on the system, it is considered a carrier.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Dormant vulnerabilities can run, but are not currently running.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Software containing dormant and carrier vulnerabilities can sometimes be uninstalled or disabled, removing the risk.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Active vulnerabilities, if distinguished from the other types, can be prioritized for patching.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerability mitigation is measures that do not close the vulnerability, but make it more difficult to exploit or reduce the consequences of an attack.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Reducing the attack surface, particularly for parts of the system with root (administrator) access, and closing off opportunities for exploits to engage in privilege exploitation is a common strategy for reducing the harm that a cyberattack can cause.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] If a patch for third-party software is unavailable, it may be possible to temporarily disable the software.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] A penetration test attempts to enter the system via an exploit to see if the system is insecure.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] If a penetration test fails, it does not necessarily mean that the system is secure.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Some penetration tests can be conducted with automated software that tests against existing exploits for known vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Other penetration tests are conducted by trained hackers.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Many companies prefer to contract out this work as it simulates an outsider attack.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] The vulnerability lifecycle begins when vulnerabilities are introduced into hardware or software.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Detection of vulnerabilities can be by the software vendor, or by a third party.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] In the latter case, it is considered most ethical to immediately disclose the vulnerability to the vendor so it can be fixed.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Government or intelligence agencies buy vulnerabilities that have not been publicly disclosed and may use them in an attack, stockpile them, or notify the vendor.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] As of 2013, the Five Eyes (United States, United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand) captured the plurality of the market and other significant purchasers included Russia, India, Brazil, Malaysia, Singapore, North Korea, and Iran.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Organized criminal groups also buy vulnerabilities, although they typically prefer exploit kits.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Even vulnerabilities that are publicly known or patched are often exploitable for an extended period.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Security patches can take months to develop, or may never be developed.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] A patch can have negative effects on the functionality of software and users may need to test the patch to confirm functionality and compatibility.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Larger organizations may fail to identify and patch all dependencies, while smaller enterprises and personal users may not install patches.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Research suggests that risk of cyberattack increases if the vulnerability is made publicly known or a patch is released.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Cybercriminals can reverse engineer the patch to find the underlying vulnerability and develop exploits, often faster than users install the patch.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Vulnerabilities become deprecated when the software or vulnerable versions fall out of use.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] This can take an extended period of time; in particular, industrial software may not be feasible to replace even if the manufacturer stops supporting it.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] A commonly used scale for assessing the severity of vulnerabilities is the open-source specification Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS).
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] CVSS evaluates the possibility to exploit the vulnerability and compromise data confidentiality, availability, and integrity.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] It also considers how the vulnerability could be used and how complex an exploit would need to be.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] The amount of access needed for exploitation and whether it could take place without user interaction are also factored in to the overall score.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Someone who discovers a vulnerability may disclose it immediately (full disclosure) or wait until a patch has been developed (responsible disclosure, or coordinated disclosure).
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] The former approach is praised for its transparency, but the drawback is that the risk of attack is likely to be increased after disclosure with no patch available.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Some vendors pay bug bounties to those who report vulnerabilities to them.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Not all companies respond positively to disclosures, as they can cause legal liability and operational overhead.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] There is no law requiring disclosure of vulnerabilities.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] If a vulnerability is discovered by a third party that does not disclose to the vendor or the public, it is called a zero-day vulnerability, often considered the most dangerous type because fewer defenses exist.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] The most commonly used vulnerability dataset is Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVE), maintained by Mitre Corporation.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] This information is shared into other databases, including the United States' National Vulnerability Database, where each vulnerability is given a risk score using Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS), Common Platform Enumeration (CPE) scheme, and Common Weakness Enumeration.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] CVE and other databases typically do not track vulnerabilities in software as a service products.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Submitting a CVE is voluntary for companies that discovered a vulnerability.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] The software vendor is usually not legally liable for the cost if a vulnerability is used in an attack, which creates an incentive to make cheaper but less secure software.
[src:cnapp/vulnerability-computing] Some companies are covered by laws, such as PCI, HIPAA, and Sarbanes-Oxley, that place legal requirements on vulnerability management.
